#6. Detect the signed checksum

Everything clear.


However, I have a regret. Imagine I become a heavy user of sigsum and I start
having a large collection of "<something>.proof" that I am keeping around for
some operational reason, like keeping track of what I have done in my systems.

I have "hello.py"
I can compute 7138d30e618745ee20d3e09b81ca45cfbf3a7db0eb526557a04d34e2ef2a5039

If I want to find all the valid ".proof" files for "hello.py" locally:

    grep -rni 7138d30e618745ee20d3e09b81ca45cfbf3a7db0eb526557a04d34e2ef2a5039

This does not work. If I still have my private key, I can reproduce signature
and search for the signature itself. However, if my private key has been lost
or if I have rotated my identity, I can not search my older ".proof" files.

If someone else, ten years in the future, inherit my collection of ".proof"
files, is it relatively safe for that person to assume that most signatures
have not been compromised (assuming PQ fud did not materialized) however it
makes it computationally intensive to search a checksum in all the ".proof"

In the example given for "hello.py" I store 3745 bytes of data, this is fine
disk is cheap, among those 2170 bytes are cosignatures, this is fine, however

    checksum=7138d30e618745ee20d3e09b81ca45cfbf3a7db0eb526557a04d34e2ef2a5039

would add 74 bytes (2%) and makes local offline search easy & cheap.

This also help if for whatever reason, the exact bytes of the signature have
been corrupted, it makes recovery easier, assuming future people knows best.


This "belt and suspenders" kind of brain worms may not be relevant to sigsum
and if so please ignore this, however in my personal taste for such systems,
I am fond of having the output bytes of my hash functions written to disk.

% nisse: Regarding #6, it's intentional that checksum is not included in the proof,
% since the verifier should have the data needed to compute it. We used to have a
% truncated checksum, but dropped that a year ago, see
% <https://git.glasklar.is/sigsum/project/documentation/-/blob/main/proposals/2024-11-proof-with-no-leaf-checksum.md>.
% To correlate checksums with a collection of proof files, you'd could use log hash +
% leaf index in the proof to get the checksum from the log (and if it's no longer
% online, you would need archived data). So that's not a trivial operation.
%
% In general, you will need an archive of all submitted data, indexed by checksum.
